replies.text:
@captainnemo6655 Well, I have often been accused of being psychic. 🤭
I'm a little confabulated by your use of the phrase "surprising trick". Seems a pretty obvious optical design, but I guess the phrase probably came from a science media puff piece. 🙄
I still think Reflecto-Refracto-Fluoresceomatic Confabulator is a more catchy name for marketing purposes, and certainly in keeping with the Dr Evil plan to take over the World. 🤗

@captainnemo6655 How about applying the fluorescent marker onto the lens sheet from a LCD screen - then the light will be bent and UV light converted into usable solar-cell photons. 
No machining involved, no mixing of resins and proper safety concerns. Just wiping the inside of the marker around on the lens sheet. 
Hmmm. I have some solar cells, LCD lens sheets - where's my markers ;ø)

@ThinkingandTinkering Yeah, that kinda makes sense, but a real time passive tracking system could run directly off the output of the cells, and even an "active" system would only need a small battery pack to keep the "brains" up when there's no sun at all.  In either case there's pretty much no power draw when the system isn't actually tracking, and a passive system could be set up with enough hysteresis that it would only track a few times every hour.

If you can improve perfomance by 20%+, guaranteed, with a tracking system, it's worth the additional complexity.

Improving imperfect incidence performance of cells is a worthwhile aim, but there's only a miniscule gain to be had (literally the only thing you can win back is light reflected from the front of the collector), the hard limit is the cosine law.  And I suspect that anything you put in front of the cell will at best cancel out its potential gain.
